  "prompt": "What are good, low-cost (or free) alternatives to Google Alerts?",
  "response": "There are several low-cost or free alternatives to Google Alerts that you can consider for monitoring mentions across the web. Here are a few options:\n\n1. **Talkwalker Alerts**: This is one of the closest alternatives to Google Alerts and works in a similar way, offering email notifications for new mentions of keywords.\n\n2. **Feedly**: Although primarily used as a content aggregator, you can set up keyword alerts and track relevant topics using its AI-driven capabilities. Feedly's free version has some limitations, but it can be a powerful tool with its premium features.\n\n3. **Mention**: Though it offers a paid plan, Mention provides real-time web and social media monitoring with a limited free plan that might be sufficient for personal use.\n\n4. **Social Mention**: A social media search and analysis platform that aggregates user-generated content from various networks and provides search results for mentions of keywords.\n\n5. **Boardreader**: This tool specializes in searching forums and discussion boards, which can complement other tools focused on web and social media monitoring.\n\n6. **Alerti**: While it offers premium plans, Alerti does have a free version that includes basic features for social listening and keyword alerts.\n\n7. **Reputation.com**: Offers a free tool for monitoring online sentiment and public perceptions of a brand or individual.\n\n8. **F5Bot**: A simple, free service that sends you email notifications when your keywords are mentioned on Reddit and Hacker News.\n\nEach of these tools has its own strengths and may be more suited to specific needs, so experimenting with a few might help you determine which one best meets your requirements.",
